text: It's fun to speculate that Biden made a Freudian slip, but I hope no one actually takes that seriously. I have a hard time sometimes distinguishing what people are thinking because part of American humor seems to be to make fun of someone, exaggerating events that occurred, just to pump people up. To give an example outside of politics, my college had a host of legends and rumors about a university in a neighboring town. We actually didn't compete in any meaningful way. They were D-II and had a way better athletics program, so we had no chance at all as we were a D-III private school with a focus on academics. Most of our sports facilities were super-old, and sports was just ill-funded. Academically, there might have been some competition, but honestly on that front, there was a lot more collaboration. They were a lot larger, so they had a wider range of classes, and students from my college would take classes at the other university. But in spite of all that, there were all sorts of stupid stories, and everyone just laughed at them and knew the stories were false. I'm not from the states, and this puzzled me a bit, but now I've live here longer, I'm sensing a pattern.

Intelligence is the ability to acquire and apply knowledge and skills, and wisdom has more to do with experience and moral judgement, depending on how you want to define it. What he actually says : 

"We have put together, and you guys did this for the Obama administration before this, i think the most extensive, inclusive voter fraud (Pause) organization in the history of american politics. What the president is trying to is discourage people from voting by implying their vote won't be counted, it can't be counted, we will challenge it. if enough people vote, it's going to overwhelm the system. You see what's happening now, you see the long, long lines and early voting, you see the millions already casting ballots. 
Don't be intimitated, if in fact you have any problem, go to (gives the adress), call the number, we have over 100 lawyers that will answer the phone if you think your vote is being challenged."

For those who struggle to understand this : this guy is 77 years old, and in multiple occurence he struggles to find his words in this interview. The moment he paused (after fraud), he clearly meant "voter fraud CONTROL organization". And here's why : he's actually talking about a voter fraud control organization RIGHT AFTER THAT. 

The voter fraud he identifies is the intimidation tactics he references, the ones being used by Trump. And he wishes to inform people that there are lawyers available to combat those tactics, so that people can actually vote without any problem. 

Whether he is right or wrong about Trump frauding, I don't care. Whether he is actually frauding, I don't care. But using this sequence to PROVE that Biden is frauding is beyond stupid, it's intellectual fraud. You can't isolate a sentence and refuse to hear the rest, then claim that the sentence is revealing of a shocking truth. text:
I'm really glad you guys did this interview and I'm supportive of Biden. One of the biggest reasons is I've seen him change his mind and positions when presented with a strong alternative. That being said, I was disheartened by his comments about the industrial animal agriculture model. Just fixing the environmental harms of chicken, hog and dairy factories isn't enough. This factory approach to animal production has destroyed family farmers, ranchers and dairy producers. I've watched it happen. It has also destroyed our relationship with the animals we are producing for our food. We need to treat these animals with respect and honor instead of packing them into confinement facilities and treating them like a cog in a giant meat and milk production machine. 
My family has farmed for over 100 years in South Dakota and while we have gotten bigger, the relationship we have with our animals and land is still a relationship of honor and respect. A few weeks ago, during harvest, a blind calf got out and wandered off. My brother and his family took over 4 hours out of a busy day to find this calf and make sure it was returned safely. They didn't make any money from those hours or advance the important work of the farm, but it was important the calf was found because we owed it to her to take care of her. She's now safely returned and lives with her seeing-eye Holstein, who  does a pretty good job of looking over her.
Our agricultural policies need to advance a model of food production based upon family farmers, ranchers and dairy producers. People who will stop what they are doing and find the lost animal.
Thank you again.

text:
To all those that say that Biden wasn't "your first choice" he really should have been.  I can like or agree with "person A" more than "person B", but the real thing that matters is will "person A" or "person B" ultimately get more of the things i feel needs to be accomplished (whether benefitting myself, my community, country, or world as a whole) or on the road to being accomplished.  And the answer to that question has been Biden right from the start. 
As and example, take healthcare. A full public "single payer" type system is much better (Bernie) than a combination "public option" (Biden).  But i realize that if Bernie was the presidential candidate it would be very likely he would not even get a chance to implement his plan, either because he would lose the election (trump base + centrist (soft) republicans (who are so scared of "socialism" and on this issue alone would abstain or reluctantly vote for trump) or if Bernie did win, it would be by such a small margin and the senate would have zero chance of being held by the democrats (and i mean zero!).  Ultimately, the result for Bernie would be no movement at all towards a  public "single payer" system and a huge number of people without adequate healthcare coverage. For Biden, not only would everyone be able to have adequate coverage (albeit not as good as it should or could be) but half the step to a full comprehensive plan would be achieved, the results would be real and visible to all the naysayers, and the next step will have that much more widespread support and be easier to achieve. 
This same thing applies to much of Biden's platform.  Right now the whole discussion surrounds "ifs" on a large scale. After four years of a Biden presidency the country as a whole can then be at a point of discussing "hows" on a more macro level. In other words, people can see that the sky didn't fall, cold war "commies" aren't coming out of the woodwork, and gramma isn't getting raped twice a month.

text: The one area I hope continues is the NASA Artemis moon missions. Lovett seems dismissive of it in a few videos. I agree it's weird to be at the top of the GOP agenda list. NASA gets 0.4% of fed budget. The current plan is to land the first woman and the next man on the Moon by 2024. That date was pushed up by Trump so it would occur during his second term. If the timeline is kept it'll keep current plans moving ahead, keep the pressure on contractors to get things done on time and on budget, etc. China is rapidly developing their plans and it'll be important to have some claim to resources on the Moon. Plus SLS needs somewhere to go (or be canceled which isn't happening). NASA keeps having to change plans when new administrations come in which ends up delaying or canceling programs and costing time and money.  Jim Bridenstine - who many were skeptical at his confirmation - has done a really good job and should be kept on. More focus on climate science and education should be added with additional funding. Trump, IIRC, canceled all or most of that to focus on the Moon program and for political reasons.

text:
In RE to the farmers part: first off you don't have a clue what you're talking about. The point is, and what the EU does is they pay farmers to not overwork their land, to ensure that first, that will help reduce soil erosion and secondly to reduce food waste and the carbon footprint. At this point, farmers are already subsidized but its currently to mass produce mostly high water usage/tillage crops (although GM crops do reduce the need for soil turnover and thus soil erosion). This isn't kickbacks, these are measure to ensure the land that is fro food production remains viable- rotating crops that was the 'old' traditional  system isn't economically feasible in a free market system anymore.  T
The other part he was referring to is that you put land aside for carbon capture. These are usually plants that can pull out CO2 from the atmosphere, use some of it, and store some within the soil. There may be better methods of carbon capture but if this is done on non-agricultural land (high acidic land with low quality soil), this might be possible. But the larger point of the whole interview is that he  illustrated he wants to find ways to reduce the US and global carbon production. 
I will finish with this, the fact that he said he wants to transition away from fossil fuels is HUGE, the political consequences of such a statement could be drastic. The media jumped on that like they were starving for anything controversial so they can appear to be neutral. In Canada, when our Prime Minister said pretty much the same thing, it was a huge controversy, and we are a more left leaning society than America. I don't think you realize the guts it took to come out and say that, and to acknowledge it.
 Granted he still wants to allow fracking which is absolutely awful, but hopefully he can be persuaded - and that's the point here. He's not perfect but he listens and indicated he wants to increase funding to help research at universities/colleges which is vital for health and the environment.

text:
‚Äã @British savvy  I consider myself an environmentalist.....I care about habitat and wildlife in particular. But the path we are taking to move away from fossil fuels is generating activity and outcomes that are more damaging that the initial problem; partly because we are implementing immature technology that is not as far down the development curve as it needs to be. When the cure is worse than the disease then you need to stop taking the medicine; particularly when the medicine does not even offer a cure in the long term, as in this instance. 

Do you appreciate the amount of damage done extracting and processing exotic metals for batteries and electric motors?; metals such as lithium and rare earths. The extraction is bad enough but the processing is immensely polluting. Refining rare earths involves cracking acids and in some instances 30 days of harsh acid refinement with many cycles. Please look it up and educate yourself.

And then we have the fact that we could not possibly generate the electricity required using renewables and if we did the vast majority of the planets surface would have to be covered in wind turbines and solar panels; nuclear is the only feasible way to do it if you want to exclude fossil fuels. And each wind turbine and solar panel comes at a massive cost in terms of the materials required, the processing energy and the pollution/damage caused as a result. 

You realise that only something like 5% of energy is delivered as electricity as we stand....95% of it is delivered as oil (cars, planes, lorries, buses etc) or gas (household/commercial heating, industrial energy etc). Hence the electricity grid only supports 5% of current energy usage....imagine what has to be done to support all the other uses of energy if they were all delivered as electricity and the amount of additional cabling required.                                                                                                                                                                                        

Like I said previously....this is either all political posturing or sheer naivety as it is not credible. I have worked in the industry for 15 years so I know.

I'm pleased Joe stressed repeatedly that he will be 'America's President' not just a Democrat, so the 'Bidencare'  mention felt like a mis-step. As many faults as there are with our National Health Service, it isn't viewed as political itself - although closures, funding, staff wages etc do clearly become politicised by either party. The notion of healthcare as a right for everyone remains in a neutral space and I hope you guys can achieve this too.

Already voted in Texas and made sure several of my friends have already voted.  In fact, got one of them to vote for the first time ever this year.  :D  I was driving her around on Super Tuesday because doctor wasn't letting her drive for a while due to health problems.  The only errand I'd set for myself that day was going to vote, and I mentioned it and why I thought it was important.  Well, she hadn't voted before, but she had apparently registered when she got her driver license and was as sick of what's been going on as I've been.  I helped her look up her precinct and we were pleased to see that our county let us vote at any polling place.  We swung by mine.  In and out in 5 minutes.  She was shocked at how easy it was.

Well, she's moved since then and is now in Dallas, but she made sure to register and sent me a pic of her own sticker in response to my "I Voted" selfie the day I finally got to vote in the general.

All that to say, that's at least one new vote that went to Biden and the Dems in the state of Texas.
